				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Chain Mezzing Casters!<a name="53279"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 22 04 3:16 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>The reasoning behind this was a pickup LDoN where I began chaining a Monkey at about 40% (somewhere between 10-40% is where they begin taking care of themselves). We had an add in camp but the Chanter had it locked down. I announce that I'm chaining and the MT decides that it's switch target time. Well needless to say, he woke the mezzed one, SA stayed on original as he knew what was going on, Chanter get's trounced, next is Druid, next is MT, monk feigns, Cleric DA's and boogies out, I fade. Small mess, but managable.
<br />

<br />
I can only blame myself for not clarifying what I was doing and why. I use this method on a regular basis with my normal group of guildmates and friends. Again, only on casters to disrupt gate or CH. My normal group includes two very talented Paladins so my actual need for this may be minimal. It's just added insurance. Plus it helps when you have a dispelling bugger to deal with. Nothing like losing all your buffs to some gimp monkey. The real nice advantage here is that in between mezzes, the numbskull tries to cast something. This give your tanks and nice opportunity to beat on it without retribution and saves the healer Mana for future use.
<br />

<br />
The long and short being, make sure everyone knows what you're doing. I don't chain until the 40% range or lower as the group will enjoy other tunes much more. Just a handy method for keeping it clean. 
<br />

<br />
btw, Howdy Drumm, good to see ya!
